Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

01:38 PM Defendant Julie L Winchel in court with attorney Katherine Cook.  Defendant Julie L Winchel in custody.  Annette M Barna appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Julie L Winchel appeared by video means with Attorney.   Waive formal reading of the CC.  State informs the court that DE was ordered to live with her mother and did not do so.  State asks for $1000.00 cash bond, absolute sobriety.  Atty Cook argues for a sign bond, DE does have a friend that she could reside with if released if his building permits this, believes DE will attend court appearances.  Friend is to contact Rusk County Housing to find out if Ms Winchel may reside with him.  

$500.00 cash bond,   Defendant is not to consume or possess alcohol.  Do not enter premises where alcohol is primary business, any bars taverns or liquor stores or any other establishment where the primary purpose is the sale of alcohol.   No possession/consumption or use of illegal or illicit drugs, or any substance intended to use to alter mental state or mood.  Not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  No possession of medications not prescribed to you by a physician. If released DE must provide an address and phone number.
